\subsection{Problem Formulation}

Given a user $u$ with interaction history $H_u$ and a candidate set
$C_u=\{c_1,\ldots,c_n\}$, the same-candidate reranking task is to order all
candidates so that the held-out next item is ranked as highly as possible. In
our formal setting, $n=101$ for every test event: one positive item and 100
negatives. Every compared method must produce one finite score per
$(u,c_i)$ pair under the same key schema.

The working scorer in \method{} (Figure~\ref{fig:framework}) is a task-grounded
candidate relevance posterior $p_i=P(y_i=1\mid H_u,c_i)$: a pointwise relevance probability that
the LLM emits when asked to judge each candidate under the next-interaction
task. Around this posterior we define an \emph{analyzed design space} of
uncertainty-adjusted ranking. We attach to each posterior an uncertainty
estimate $U_i\in[0,1]$ and define a one-parameter ranking family
\begin{equation}
    r_i = p_i(1-U_i)^\eta ,
    \label{eq:risk-score}
\end{equation}
where the risk exponent $\eta$ is fixed or selected using validation data only.
When $\eta=0$, the score reduces to the bare relevance posterior. We treat this
family as a hypothesis to be tested rather than as validated machinery: the
ablations in Section~\ref{sec:results} ask whether any positive $\eta$ or any
uncertainty term improves same-candidate ranking, and we report that they do
not. The $\eta=0$ row is test-best in all four domains, so the relevance
posterior itself is the operative ranking signal and the risk term is retained
only as an analyzed, and empirically inert, design choice.

The formulation is intentionally limited to reranking. It assumes a candidate
set has already been generated and asks whether a pointwise language-model
relevance posterior orders the same candidates more reliably than existing
LLM-based scoring and representation baselines. This choice gives the method a
narrow but auditable contract: for every event, each candidate must receive
exactly one posterior, one uncertainty value, and one final score before the
shared importer computes metrics.

\subsection{Task-Grounded Candidate Evidence}

For each user-candidate pair, the LLM is asked to evaluate the candidate under
the next-interaction task rather than under a generic similarity task. The
signal row records a pointwise relevance probability, a model-reported adjusted
probability, evidence support, counterevidence strength, and a short rationale.
The relevance probability is the working ranking score; the remaining fields
feed the analyzed uncertainty design space. The prompt does not reveal the
positive item index or test label.

The signal package is reproducible at the artifact level. Provenance records
the generation command, split-specific task paths, parser-compatible schema,
row counts, parse-failure count, and hashes for the signal and candidate
files. Rows with invalid probability, support, counterevidence, or key fields
are rejected before score export. The formal packages used for the paper pass

=== EXPERIMENTS ===
\section{Experiments}
\label{sec:experiments}

\subsection{Experimental Setup}

\paragraph{Datasets and Candidate Protocol.} We evaluate on eight Amazon
product-review domains: Beauty, Books, Electronics, Movies, Sports, Toys, Home,
and Tools. Each domain uses a 101-candidate same-candidate task with 10,000 test
users, except Beauty, whose smaller catalog yields 973 eligible test users.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\small
\caption{Dataset statistics. All domains use the same 101-candidate
same-candidate task (one positive, 100 popularity-sampled negatives); Beauty has
a smaller test-user pool because of its catalog size.}
\label{tab:datasets}
\begin{tabular}{lrrr}
\toprule
Domain & Test Users & Candidates/User & Candidate Rows \\
\midrule
Beauty & 973 & 101 & 98,273 \\
Books & 10,000 & 101 & 1,010,000 \\
Electronics & 10,000 & 101 & 1,010,000 \\
Movies & 10,000 & 101 & 1,010,000 \\
Sports & 10,000 & 101 & 1,010,000 \\
Toys & 10,000 & 101 & 1,010,000 \\
Home & 10,000 & 101 & 1,010,000 \\
Tools & 10,000 & 101 & 1,010,000 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Each test instance consists of one ground-truth next item and 100 negatives.
The same candidate rows are shared by all methods; no method receives a
different negative set or a different candidate order as an advantage. The
positive item is hidden from the scoring prompt and from the baseline scoring
wrappers. Validation rows are used only for selection or calibration decisions
declared in advance, while test rows are reserved for final reporting and
paired tests.

The task package keeps validation and test artifacts separate. Each domain has
train-history files for the corresponding task split, validation ranking rows
for selection, test ranking rows for final reporting, and a test
\texttt{candidate\_items.csv} file that defines the exact key set every
paper-facing score file must cover. This separation prevents validation
selection code from silently reading test histories and prevents a method from
entering the table with a different candidate universe.

A result is table-eligible only if its score file exactly matches the candidate
key set, has no duplicate or missing keys, contains finite numeric scores, and
passes the local/server provenance checks. The score contract is deliberately
minimal:
\[
(\texttt{source\_event\_id},\texttt{user\_id},\texttt{item\_id},\texttt{score}).
\]
This contract lets official baselines keep their native training objective
while forcing their final candidate scores through the same metric code.

\paragraph{Backbone and Fairness Policy.} All methods use Qwen3-8B whenever an
LLM or LLM-derived representation is required. Baseline-specific adapters,
checkpoints, graph modules, intent modules, or representation learners are
preserved when they are part of the official algorithm. We do not retune every
baseline on the test split; the primary comparison uses official default or
recommended baseline hyperparameters, while \method{} uses fixed or
validation-controlled settings. Full-catalog metrics reported by upstream
repositories are not imported into the paper table.

\paragraph{Baselines.} In every domain we compare against the same eight
official-code-level LLM-based recommendation baselines:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{ELMRec}~\cite{elmrec}: High-order interaction-aware LLM recommendation
    \item \textbf{IRLLRec}~\cite{irllrec}: Intent representation learning with LLMs
    \item \textbf{LLM2Rec}~\cite{llm2rec}: LLM embedding with sequential recommendation
    \item \textbf{LLMEmb}~\cite{llmemb}: LLM-generated embeddings for recommendation
    \item \textbf{LLM-ESR}~\cite{llmesr}: LLM-enhanced long-tailed sequential recommendation
    \item \textbf{ProEx}~\cite{proex}: Profile extrapolation with LLMs
    \item \textbf{ProMax}~\cite{promax}: LLM-derived profiles with distribution shaping\footnote{ProEx (arXiv:2512.00679) and ProMax (arXiv:2604.26231) are recent preprints (to appear) from the ProRec line, released through the shared official repository \texttt{BlueGhostYi/ProRec}; we include them as strong recent profile-based baselines and adapt their official shared code under our unified protocol.}
    \item \textbf{RLMRec}~\cite{rlmrec}: Representation learning with LLMs
\end{itemize}

Baselines use official default or recommended hyperparameters unless a
documented bridge is required by the unified protocol. Each row must record the
official repository, pinned commit, adaptation mode, checkpoint or
representation artifact when applicable, score path, score hash, and coverage
audit. Test-set model selection is forbidden for both baselines and \method.

\input{tables/baseline_provenance_summary}

\paragraph{Metrics and Statistics.} We report HR@$k$ and NDCG@$k$ for
$k\in\{5,10,20\}$, plus MRR. The paired unit is the user event: for each
method and metric, we compare the per-event score of \method{} with the
corresponding per-event score of an official baseline. For each domain,
\method{} is compared against each official baseline on all seven metrics,
yielding 56 paired tests (8 baselines $\times$ 7 metrics). We use paired
event bootstrap confidence intervals with 2,000 bootstrap samples, 95\%
percentile intervals, and Holm correction at $\alpha=0.05$ over the full
family of 56 tests in that domain. The Holm-corrected paired tests are
reported for all eight domains, including the two where \method{} does not
rank first (Beauty, Movies), so that the losses carry the same paired
uncertainty as the wins; Table~\ref{tab:significance_summary} gives the signed
counts (ahead / behind / non-significant) out of 56 per domain.

\paragraph{Cost and Latency.} \method{} requires one LLM forward pass per
candidate to obtain its per-candidate relevance posterior, i.e.\ 101 scoring
calls per user and roughly $1.01$M scoring calls per 10,000-user domain (we
batch these through vLLM). This is a same-candidate reranking cost incurred at
scoring time; the present paper audits ranking quality and evidence integrity
and does \emph{not} optimise online serving latency, per-token cost, or online
batching (cf.\ the LLM cost-and-latency limitation in \S\ref{sec:analysis}).

\paragraph{Evidence Packaging.} Every completed row has a lightweight local
evidence package with metrics, row counts, provenance, score audits, logs, and
server manifest hashes. Large score files, prediction files, checkpoints, and
embeddings remain server-side unless an archive decision requires otherwise.
This separation keeps the GitHub artifact small while preserving enough hashes
and row counts to detect missing or accidentally cleaned evidence. The
paper-facing ledger contains 72 rows: 64 official baseline rows (eight
baselines $\times$ eight domains) and eight \method{} rows.

\paragraph{Diagnostic Modules.} The main comparison is accompanied by three
paper-critical diagnostics, run on the four domains (Sports, Toys, Home, Tools)
for which the full per-event signal rows are packaged locally. The observation
module bins events by C-CRP uncertainty and checks whether higher uncertainty
corresponds to lower ranking reliability. The component module evaluates
leave-one-component-out variants under the frozen same-candidate protocol. The
hyperparameter module sweeps real controls, especially $\eta$ and the
uncertainty weight grid, with validation-only selection and reporting-only test
curves. These diagnostics are not allowed to replace the main official-baseline
comparison.

\subsection{Main Results}

\input{tables/main_results}

=== RESULTS (Backbone Robustness subsection, lines 217-295) ===
\subsection{Backbone Robustness: Two Additional LLMs Across All Eight Domains}
\label{sec:second_backbone}

The attribution above establishes \emph{which signal} carries the headline---the
task-grounded pointwise posterior---but not whether that signal is specific to
one backbone. To test this we re-run the \emph{identical} same-candidate pipeline
under two additional different-family frozen LLMs---Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct and
Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3---changing only the scoring model and holding the
protocol fixed (10{,}000 users / Beauty $973$, 101 candidates, the same panels,
score schema, and seeded tie-break). This yields a full
$3\,\text{backbones}\times 8\,\text{domains}$ grid
(Table~\ref{tab:three_backbone}): a substantially broader robustness probe than
the single-backbone, few-domain checks common in LLM-for-recommendation work,
which typically vary only one backbone over a handful of representative Amazon
domains \citep{xu2025slmrec}.

\textbf{The ranking advantage survives frozen-model substitution.} Across the
six domains where the Qwen3-8B posterior ranks first over all eight official
baselines, Mistral-7B \emph{also} ranks first in all six, and Llama-3.1-8B in
five---the lone exception being Books, where the Llama posterior ($0.2710$) trails
the strongest baseline LLMEmb ($0.2737$) by $1.0\%$, which we report rather than
round away. In aggregate $17$ of the $18$ backbone$\,\times\,$(winning-domain)
cells clear the strongest official baseline---both per-backbone deltas are shown in
Table~\ref{tab:three_backbone}: Mistral improves on it by $+7.8\%$
to $+24.4\%$ and Llama by $-1.0\%$ (Books) to $+34.2\%$ (Electronics). Crucially,
the two domains where Qwen is honestly \emph{not} first (Beauty, $\#2$; Movies,
$\#5$) remain below the strongest baseline under \emph{both} additional backbones
as well, so the full \emph{win/loss partition}---six wins and two losses, not the
average---transfers (the added backbones are weaker in \emph{level} on the two
losing domains, so we claim transfer of the domain-level partition, not of exact
ranks or effect sizes). We also observe that the \emph{absolute} level tracks
backbone capability---Qwen3-8B strongest, Mistral-7B and Llama-3.1-8B typically
$\sim 10\text{--}25\%$ lower---an observation consistent with, though not proof of,
the headline being a \emph{ranking} advantage that a stronger frozen LLM expresses
more sharply rather than an artefact of any one model. We are deliberate about
scope: the official baselines are held at their unified-backbone comparison values
while only C-CRP's scoring LLM is swapped, so this establishes that \emph{C-CRP's
posterior signal stays competitive under frozen-model substitution}, not a
re-tuned cross-backbone SOTA result. The single sub-baseline winning-domain cell
(Llama on Books) is an absolute NDCG@10 gap of $0.2737 - 0.2710 = 0.0027$, a margin
small enough that we do not read this cell as a stable below-baseline finding; we
rest the claim at the domain level---$17/18$ cells across two unrelated model
families---rather than on any one cell. We also do not claim to disentangle two
distinct sources of the Beauty/Movies losses: it is consistent with the data that
those two domains are intrinsically harder for this protocol (all three frozen
backbones land below the strongest baseline, with the same loss direction), and
also consistent that the added backbones are simply weaker scorers in absolute
terms; the present table does not separate these. The same pointwise scoring
code, score schema, and tie-break are shared across all three backbones, so each
substitution isolates the backbone as the only changed factor.

\textbf{A backbone-specific deep-recall diagnostic.} The replication also exposes
a model-specific failure mode that we measure rather than leave qualitative. The
Llama posterior cedes the deepest-recall metric (HR@20) to LLMEmb on several
domains. Grouping each $101$-candidate event, the Llama verbalized posterior
floors $84$--$90\%$ of candidates at exactly $0.0$, against $19$--$34\%$ for Qwen,
and floors the \emph{ground-truth positive} in $53$--$78\%$ of events (Qwen
$6$--$20\%$). A floored positive lands in a large zero-score tie block whose
expected rank pushes it past $20$, which is precisely a deep-recall loss; yet on
the $10$--$16\%$ of candidates Llama does grade it remains discriminative, so the
top of the ranking---NDCG, MRR, HR@5---stays sharp (hence the near-universal
NDCG@10 rank-1 result above). This also supplies the rationale for ranking by the \emph{raw} posterior
($\eta{=}0$): a risk re-weighting acts on the graded structure of the posterior,
and a backbone that floors $\sim 85$--$90\%$ of scores offers almost no graded
signal for such a term to exploit. This is a plausible diagnostic explanation, not
a re-derivation: it supports the conservative choice of ranking by the raw
posterior on the additional backbones and is consistent with the $\eta{=}0$-best
negative result of Section~\ref{sec:results}, but it does \emph{not} by itself
re-establish that result for every backbone; a full risk-instrumented $\eta$ sweep
per backbone is left to future work.

